nstruct an ethics beyond anything Foucault ever attempted while remaining consistent with his core postulates. It advances the concept of ‘life continuance’, which expresses a normative orientation to the future in terms of the quest for survival and well-being, giving rise to irreducible normative values as part of the discursive order of events. This approach is explored in contrast with a range of other, established systems, from the Kantian to the Marxist, contract ethics and utilitarianism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNormativity (Ethics). 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aEthics.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aHeidegger.  aKant.  aMarx and Hegel.  aMichel Foucault.  aMoral philosophy.  aNormativity.  aPluralism.  aPoststructuralism.1 aOlssen, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615661740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526156617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526156617/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles